FIX — FulfillmentRecord must track per-item, not per-receipt

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
CONTEXT
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

app/models/fulfillment_record.py currently has a UNIQUE constraint on
etsy_receipt_id alone. This is wrong: a single Etsy receipt can
contain multiple transactions (multiple different listing_id's bought
in one order). With the current design, once ANY transaction from a
receipt creates a FulfillmentRecord, every OTHER transaction in that
same receipt is incorrectly treated as "already handled" by the
idempotency check in EtsyReceiptWorker, and its Printify order is
never submitted. This silently drops real physical fulfillment for
any multi-item POD order — a correctness bug, not a scale limitation.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
FIX
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. In app/models/fulfillment_record.py: change the unique constraint
   from etsy_receipt_id alone to a composite unique constraint on
   (etsy_receipt_id, etsy_transaction_id) — add an etsy_transaction_id
   column if it doesn't already exist (each transaction within a
   receipt has its own transaction_id in Etsy's ShopReceipt response —
   confirm the exact field name from the ShopReceipt schema, likely
   nested under a transactions array per receipt).

2. In app/workers/etsy_receipt_worker.py: update the idempotency check
   to query on (etsy_receipt_id, etsy_transaction_id) together, not
   etsy_receipt_id alone. Update the loop so it iterates every
   transaction within a receipt independently — each transaction gets
   its own idempotency check and, if it matches a PODProduct's
   etsy_listing_id and doesn't already have a FulfillmentRecord, its
   own separate submit_order() call.

3. Update app/services/pod_fulfillment_service.py's submit_order()
   signature/callers if needed to accept and store the
   etsy_transaction_id alongside etsy_receipt_id.

4. Update scripts/test_step81_pod_fulfillment.py to add a new test
   case: a single fake receipt containing TWO transactions for two
   DIFFERENT PODProduct-linked listings. Assert that BOTH transactions
   produce their own FulfillmentRecord and both trigger their own
   submit_order() call — this is the exact scenario the original test
   suite didn't cover and where the bug would have been caught.

5. Also add a test case for the existing single-item idempotency
   check (same receipt + same transaction processed twice = still
   only 1 record) to confirm the fix didn't break that guarantee.

Run scripts/test_step81_pod_fulfillment.py and confirm all tests pass,
including the two new ones.

